{"title_page": "The Forest of Anyk\u0161\u010diai", "text_new": "'''''The Forest of Anyk\u0161\u010diai''''' ({{lang-lt|Anyk\u0161\u010di\u0173 \u0161ilelis}}), written by [[Antanas Baranauskas]] and published in 1861 by [[Laurynas Ivinskis]], is a landmark poem in the history of the [[Lithuanian literature]].<ref name=litu>{{cite web|title=A Note of Oppositional Discourses in Baranauskas's Anyk\u0161\u010di\u0173 \u0160ilelis|author=Wendell Mayo |publisher=[[Lituanus]]|url=http://www.lituanus.org/1999/99_1_01.htm|accessdate=2009-12-16}}</ref><ref name=ant>{{cite web|title=ANYK\u0160\u010cI\u0172 \u0160ILELIS - The forest of Anyk\u0161\u010diai|url=http://www.antologija.lt/texts/17/main.html|publisher=Lithuanian Classical Literature Anthology, sponsored by [[UNESCO]]|accessdate=2009-12-16}}</ref>\n\nThe poem expresses the long-standing connection between the Lithuanian people and their forests.<ref name=ant/> It was inspired by poetry of [[Adam Mickiewicz]] and bears similarities to the [[Romantic poetry|romantic]] poetry of [[Wordsworth]] and similar works of the early 19th century, but conveys additional meanings related to the perceived oppression of the country during its 19th-century inclusion in the [[Russian Empire]].<ref name=litu/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{in lang|lt}} [http://poezija.sdf-eu.org/baran1.html Lithuanian text of poem]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080514072639/http://members.efn.org/~valdas/baranauskas.html English translation by Peter Tempest]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Forest of Anyksciai, The}}\n[[Category:1861 poems]]\n[[Category:Lithuanian literature]]\n[[Category:Lithuanian poems]]\n", "text_old": "'''''The Forest of Anyk\u0161\u010diai''''' ({{lang-lt|Anyk\u0161\u010di\u0173 \u0161ilelis}}), written by [[Antanas Baranauskas]] and published in 1861 by [[Laurynas Ivinskis]], is a landmark poem in the history of the [[Lithuanian literature]].<ref name=litu>{{cite web|title=A Note of Oppositional Discourses in Baranauskas's Anyk\u0161\u010di\u0173 \u0160ilelis|author=Wendell Mayo |publisher=[[Lituanus]]|url=http://www.lituanus.org/1999/99_1_01.htm|accessdate=2009-12-16}}</ref><ref name=ant>{{cite web|title=ANYK\u0160\u010cI\u0172 \u0160ILELIS - The forest of Anyk\u0161\u010diai|url=http://www.antologija.lt/texts/17/main.html|publisher=Lithuanian Classical Literature Anthology, sponsored by [[UNESCO]]|accessdate=2009-12-16}}</ref>\n\nThe poem expresses the long-standing connection between the Lithuanian people and their forests.<ref name=ant/> It was inspired by poetry of [[Adam Mickiewicz]] and bears similarities to the [[Romantic poetry|romantic]] poetry of [[Wordsworth]] and similar works of the early 19th century, but conveys additional meanings related to the perceived oppression of the country during its 19th-century inclusion in the [[Russian Empire]].<ref name=litu/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{in lang|lt}} [http://poezija.sdf-eu.org/baran1.html Lithuanian text of poem]\n* [http://members.efn.org/~valdas/baranauskas.html English translation by Peter Tempest]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Forest of Anyksciai, The}}\n[[Category:1861 poems]]\n[[Category:Lithuanian literature]]\n[[Category:Lithuanian poems]]\n", "name_user": "Diespiter", "label": "safe", "comment": "replaced dead link with the archive.org equivalent", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Forest_of_Anyk%C5%A1%C4%8Diai"}
